[src:grafana/grafana-latest] Query, transform, visualize, and understand your data no matter where it’s stored.
[src:grafana/grafana-latest] Easily collect, correlate, and visualize data to make informed decisions in real-time.
[src:grafana/grafana-latest] Explore your data using a query instead of creating a dashboard.
[src:grafana/grafana-latest] Learn about problems in your systems moments after they occur.
[src:grafana/grafana-latest] Perform administrative tasks such as configuring user management and roles and permissions.
[src:grafana/grafana-latest] Upgrade Grafana to stay current with the latest fixes and enhancements.
[src:grafana/grafana] Torkel Odegaard released Grafana in January 2014 as an outgrowth of work on Graphite (software) at Orbitz.
[src:grafana/grafana] The user interface was originally based on version 3 of Kibana.
[src:grafana/grafana] The company behind the project, initially named Raintank, rebranded as Grafana Labs and has raised over $500 million in venture capital funding, reaching a $6 billion valuation in 2024.
[src:grafana/grafana] Since 2021, Grafana has been licensed under the AGPLv3 (previously Apache 2.0).
[src:grafana/grafana] Grafana Labs provides two commercial Grafana offerings: Grafana Cloud for managed deployments and Grafana Enterprise for self-managed environments.
[src:grafana/grafana] Grafana Cloud provides hosted Grafana, managed telemetry services, and additional capabilities such as Adaptive Telemetry for telemetry optimization and Grafana Assistant for AI-assisted observability workflows.
[src:grafana/grafana] Grafana Enterprise contains features including LDAP team synchronization, data source permissions, and reporting.
[src:grafana/grafana] Grafana was first released in January 2014, initially targeting Graphite and InfluxDB as data sources.
[src:grafana/grafana] It later added support for relational databases including MySQL, PostgreSQL, and Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:grafana/grafana] Grafana Labs was founded in 2014 as Raintank and later adopted the name, Grafana, which combines Graphite and Kibana.
[src:grafana/grafana] The company raised $24 million in Series A funding in 2019, $50 million in Series B in 2020, $220 million in Series C in 2021 (at a $3 billion valuation), and $270 million in 2024 at a $6 billion valuation.
[src:grafana/grafana] Grafana's backend is written in Go and its frontend in TypeScript using React.
[src:grafana/grafana] The application runs as a single binary that serves a web interface and connects to external data sources through a plugin system.
[src:grafana/grafana] Plugins fall into three categories: data source plugins (for querying backends), panel plugins (for visualization types), and app plugins (for bundled functionality).
[src:grafana/grafana] Grafana does not store metrics data itself.
[src:grafana/grafana] It queries external data sources at render time and can combine data from multiple sources in a single dashboard.
[src:grafana/grafana] Built-in data source support includes Prometheus, Graphite, InfluxDB, Elasticsearch, OpenSearch, Loki, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and Splunk.
[src:grafana/grafana] Dashboards are defined as JSON documents and can be provisioned from files, version-controlled, and shared via Grafana's public dashboard library.
[src:grafana/grafana] Alerting rules can be defined against any data source, with notifications routed to email, Slack, PagerDuty, and other channels.
[src:grafana/grafana] Grafana is used by Wikimedia's infrastructure, NASA, and the Tour de France (for real-time race telemetry).
[src:grafana/introduction] Grafana open source software enables you to query, visualize, alert on, and explore your metrics, logs, and traces wherever they are stored.
[src:grafana/introduction] Grafana OSS provides you with tools to turn your time-series database (TSDB) data into insightful graphs and visualizations.
[src:grafana/introduction] The Grafana OSS plugin framework also enables you to connect other data sources like NoSQL/SQL databases, ticketing tools like Jira or ServiceNow, and CI/CD tooling like GitLab.
[src:grafana/introduction] After you’ve installed Grafana and set up your first dashboard using instructions in Getting started with Grafana, you will have many options to choose from depending on your requirements.
[src:grafana/introduction] For example, if you want to view weather data and statistics about your smart home, then you can create a playlist.
[src:grafana/introduction] If you are the administrator for an enterprise and are managing Grafana for multiple teams, then you can set up provisioning and authentication.
[src:grafana/introduction] The following sections provide an overview of Grafana features and links to product documentation to help you learn more.
[src:grafana/introduction] For more guidance and ideas, check out our Grafana Community forums.
[src:grafana/introduction] Explore your data through ad-hoc queries and dynamic drilldown.
[src:grafana/introduction] Split view and compare different time ranges, queries and data sources side by side.
[src:grafana/introduction] If you’re using Grafana Alerting, then you can have alerts sent through a number of different alert notifiers, including PagerDuty, SMS, email, VictorOps, OpsGenie, or Slack.
[src:grafana/introduction] Alert hooks allow you to create different notifiers with a bit of code if you prefer some other channels of communication.
[src:grafana/introduction] Visually define alert rules for your most important metrics.
[src:grafana/introduction] Annotate graphs with rich events from different data sources.
[src:grafana/introduction] Hover over events to see the full event metadata and tags.
[src:grafana/introduction] This feature, which shows up as a graph marker in Grafana, is useful for correlating data in case something goes wrong.
[src:grafana/introduction] You can create the annotations manually—just control-click on a graph and input some text—or you can fetch data from any data source.
[src:grafana/introduction] Refer to Annotations for more information.
[src:grafana/introduction] Discover hundreds of dashboards and plugins in the official library.
[src:grafana/introduction] Thanks to the passion and momentum of community members, new ones are added every week.
[src:grafana/introduction] Template variables allow you to create dashboards that can be reused for lots of different use cases.
[src:grafana/introduction] Values aren’t hard-coded with these templates, so for instance, if you have a production server and a test server, you can use the same dashboard for both.
[src:grafana/introduction] Templating allows you to drill down into your data, say, from all data to North America data, down to Texas data, and beyond.
[src:grafana/introduction] You can also share these dashboards across teams within your organization—or if you create a great dashboard template for a popular data source, you can contribute it to the whole community to customize and use.
[src:grafana/introduction] If you’re a Grafana administrator, then you’ll want to thoroughly familiarize yourself with Grafana configuration options and the Grafana CLI.
[src:grafana/introduction] Configuration covers both config files and environment variables.
[src:grafana/introduction] You can set up default ports, logging levels, email IP addresses, security, and more.
[src:grafana/introduction] While it’s easy to click, drag, and drop to create a single dashboard, power users in need of many dashboards will want to automate the setup with a script.
[src:grafana/introduction] For example, if you’re spinning up a new Kubernetes cluster, you can also spin up a Grafana automatically with a script that would have the right server, IP address, and data sources preset and locked in so users cannot change them.
[src:grafana/introduction] It’s also a way of getting control over a lot of dashboards.
[src:grafana/introduction] Refer to Provisioning for more information.
[src:grafana/introduction] Grafana supports different authentication methods, such as LDAP and OAuth, and allows you to map users to organizations.
[src:grafana/introduction] Refer to the User authentication overview for more information.
[src:grafana/introduction] In Grafana Enterprise, you can also map users to teams: If your company has its own authentication system, Grafana allows you to map the teams in your internal systems to teams in Grafana.
[src:grafana/introduction] That way, you can automatically give people access to the dashboards designated for their teams.
[src:grafana/introduction] Refer to Grafana Enterprise for more information.
[src:grafana/introduction] When organizations have one Grafana and multiple teams, they often want the ability to both keep things separate and share dashboards.
[src:grafana/introduction] You can create a team of users and then set permissions on folders and dashboards, and down to the data source level if you’re using Grafana Enterprise.
[src:grafana/introduction] Use the right place to ask questions, report problems, and propose changes.
[src:grafana/introduction] For more information, refer to Contribute to Grafana.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Dashboards allow you to query, transform, visualize, and understand your data no matter where it’s stored.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] A Grafana dashboard is a set of one or more panels, organized and arranged into one or more rows or tabs, that provide an at-a-glance view of related information.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] These panels are created using components that query and transform raw data from a data source into visualizations.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] A data source can be an SQL database, Grafana Loki, Grafana Mimir, or an API endpoint.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Data source plugins take a query you want answered, retrieve the data from the data source, and reconcile the differences between the data model of the data source and the data model of Grafana dashboards.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Queries allow you to reduce the entirety of your data to a specific dataset, providing a more manageable visualization.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Since data sources have their own distinct query languages, Grafana dashboards provide you with a query editor to accommodate these differences.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] A panel is the container that displays the visualization and provides you with various controls to manipulate it.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Panel options let you customize many aspects of a visualization and the options differ based on which visualization you select.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] When the data format in a visualization doesn’t meet your requirements, you can apply a transformation that manipulates the data returned by a query.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] With 150+ data source plugins, you can unify all your data sources into a single dashboard to streamline data monitoring and troubleshooting.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] With Grafana, you can translate, transform, and visualize data in flexible and versatile dashboards.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Get step-by-step directions for how to create or import your first dashboard and modify dashboard settings.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Learn about reusable library panels, dashboard links, annotations, and dashboard JSON.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Learn about dashboard and folder management, as well as generative AI features for dashboards.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Add variables to metric queries and panel titles to create interactive and dynamic dashboards.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Automatically generate and share PDF reports from your Grafana dashboards.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Share Grafana dashboards and panels using links, snapshots, embeds, and exports.
[src:grafana/latest-dashboards] Share your dashboards with anyone without requiring access to your Grafana organization.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] Easily collect, correlate, and visualize data so you can make informed decisions in real time.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] Panels are the basic building block in Grafana dashboards, composed of a query and a visualization, a graphical representation of query results.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] Visualizations provide you several different ways to present your data within a panel, depending on what best suits the data and your needs.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] Grafana’s growing suite of visualizations, ranging from time series graphs to heatmaps to cutting-edge 3D charts, help you decode complex datasets.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] Panels offer a wide variety of formatting and styling options from applying colors based on field values to custom units.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] Each visualization also comes with options specific to it that give you further control over how your data is displayed.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] With Grafana panels and visualizations, you can easily get the information you need from your data and optimize performance.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] Learn about all the visualizations available in Grafana, including which visualizations are ideal for different datasets and how to configure their options.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] Learn about the features of the panel editor and how to begin editing a panel.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] Learn about configuring standard options like units, field display names, and colors.
[src:grafana/panels-visualizations] Learn about querying and transforming your data to refine your visualizations.
